04237nam a22004335i 9780804765800DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221992cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047658007 a10.1515/97808047658002doi  a(DE-B1597)581781  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aDiPiero, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDangerous Truths and Criminal Passions :bThe Evolution of the French Novel, 1569-1791 /cThomas DiPiero. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (412 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. The Construction of a Genre -- tChapter 1 The Rise of Aristocratic Fiction -- tChapter 2 The Ideology of Realism in the Early Seventeenth Century -- tChapter 3 Polexandre and the Politics of Heroic Fiction -- tChapter 4 The Alienation and Commodification of the Novel -- tPart Two. The Development of the Modern Novel -- tChapter 5 Le Roman bourgeois and the Modern Novel -- tChapter 6 A Discourse of One's Own: La Princesse de Clèeves -- tChapter 7 Mastery and Seduction in Eighteenth-Century Fiction -- tChapter 8 "Burn the Letter!": La Religieuse -- tChapter 9 Justine and the Discourse of the (Other) Master -- tAfterword -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book challenges several traditional assumptions about the development of the French novel, notably that the novel is a bourgeois art form that rose and flourished along with the rise of the bourgeoisie; and that the novels of the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries were inevitable stepping stones on the road to the apotheosis of realism realized in the novels of Balzac, Flaubert, and Zola. Instead, the author argues that the early French novel articulated the French aristocracy's claims to natural ascendancy against an encroaching middle class. But like any other literary form, the novel produces and is a product of ideology, and it reveals the contradictions lying beneath the surface of an apparently seamless social structure. After the death of Louis XIV and the resulting social and political redefinition of the aristocracy, the ideological rifts in the novel's form enabled it to shift its class affiliations with the changing times. French cultural life was increasingly tinged with values determined by new configurations in the control and transmission of property, including new constraints on women's sexual behavior. Fiction that claimed for itself a rightful place in the real world began to appear. As it had during the seventeenth century, fiction continued to negotiate complex social contradictions and label as malevolent any person or group that seemed to threaten social order, notably the immoderate woman who flouted traditional conceptions of virtue and threatened to read the social fabric. This new account of the rise of the French novel is enriched throughout by close readings of both well-known and obscure novels, including d'Urfe;'s L'Astre;e, Gomberville's Polexandre, Furetière's Le Roman bourgeois, Pre;vost's Manon Lescaut, Diderot's La Religieuse, and Sade's Justine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLiterary Studies -- General Criticism and Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476580040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804765800423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804765800/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles